member.name: M:AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnSystem.Transform(System.Object,AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnSystem,AGI.STKUtil.IAgCartesian3Vector)
member.summary:
Translates the position vector from this system into the output system.
Consider a point moving along its trajectory in space. The point's position and velocity can be given at some specified time using Cartesian coordinates in one of VGT coordinate systems. The same point at the same time will have different Cartesian coordinates with respect to a different VGT coordinate system. One set of coordinates can be obtained from the other using Transform methods defined for VGT coordinate systems: given time and coordinates with respect to one VGT coordinate system, these methods output coordinates with respect to another system. For example, consider a center point of a satellite. Its location in low Earth orbit can be given using Cartesian coordinates with respect to the ECEF coordinate system (ECEF means Earth Centered Earth Fixed). The same location is significantly farther away from the center of the Moon so its Cartesian coordinates in the Moon Centered Moon Fixed coordinate system will reflect a much greater distance from the Moon center.

param.name: Epoch
param.para: Specify an epoch. The method may throw an exception if the epoch parameter specified cannot be converted to a currently selected date unit.

param.name: OutputSystem
param.para: Specify a system to transform the position to.

member.summary: Translates the position and rate vectors from this system into the output system.

member.name: M:AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnAxes.Transform(System.Object,AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnAxes,AGI.STKUtil.IAgCartesian3Vector)
member.summary:
Transforms the input vector from this axes into the output axes.
Consider a vector rotating and changing its magnitude in space. The vector's direction and magnitude as well as its time rate of change can be given at some specified time using Cartesian coordinates in one of VGT coordinate axes. The same vector at the same time will have different Cartesian coordinates with respect to different VGT coordinate axes. One set of coordinates can be obtained from the other using Transform methods defined for VGT coordinate axes: given time and coordinates with respect to one VGT coordinate axes, these methods output coordinates with respect to other axes. For example, consider a position vector of a satellite defined as displacement vector between the center of the Earth and the center of the satellite. When this position vector is viewed with respect to the Moon fixed axes, its magnitude remains the same because the vector is still a displacement vector between the Earth center and the center of satellite. Its Cartesian coordinates with respect to the Moon fixed axes will be different but not its magnitude.

param.name: Epoch
param.para: Specify an epoch. The method may throw an exception if the epoch parameter specified cannot be converted to a currently selected date unit.

param.name: OutputAxes
param.para: Specify an axes the input vector is transformed into.

member.summary: Transforms the input vector and vector's rate from this axes into the output axes.

member.name: F:AGI.STKVgt.AgECrdnTrajectoryAxesType.eCrdnTrajectoryAxesICR
member.summary: Intrack Crosstrack Radial Axes. The Z axis is outward along the position vector (radial); the Y axis is along the cross product of the position and velocity (crosstrack); the X axis is in the direction of motion and constructed as Y x Z (intrack).

member.name: F:AGI.STKVgt.AgECrdnTrajectoryAxesType.eCrdnTrajectoryAxesVNC
member.summary: Velocity - Normal - Co-normal Axes. The X axis is along the velocity vector; the Y axis is along the cross product of the position and velocity (normal); the Z axis is constructed as X x Y (co-normal).

member.name: F:AGI.STKVgt.AgECrdnTrajectoryAxesType.eCrdnTrajectoryAxesRIC
member.summary: Radial Intrack Crosstrack Axes. The X axis is outward along the position vector (radial); the Z axis is along the cross product of the position and velocity (crosstrack); the Y axis is in the direction of motion and is constructed as Z x X (intrack).

member.name: F:AGI.STKVgt.AgECrdnTrajectoryAxesType.eCrdnTrajectoryAxesLVLH
member.summary: Local Vertical, Local Horizontal Axes. The X axis is along the position vector (local vertical); the Z axis is along the cross product of the position and velocity; the Y axis is in the direction of motion and constructed as Z x X (local horizontal).

member.name: F:AGI.STKVgt.AgECrdnTrajectoryAxesType.eCrdnTrajectoryAxesVVLH
member.summary: Vehicle Velocity, Local Horizontal Axes. The Z axis is along the negative position vector; the Y axis is along the negative cross product of the position and velocity (local horizontal); the X axis is constructed as Z x Y (toward velocity).

member.name: F:AGI.STKVgt.AgECrdnTrajectoryAxesType.eCrdnTrajectoryAxesBBR
member.summary: Body-to-body Rotating Axes. The X axis is along the negative position vector; the Z axis is along the cross product of the position and velocity; the Y axis is constructed as Z x X.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnPointGrazing
member.summary: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the selected central body along a defined direction.

remarks.para: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the selected central body along a defined direction. To define a grazing point, start by defining a reference point which will serve as the starting location for the line along which the grazing point will be computed. Next define a direction to be used in conjunction with the position vector from the selected central body to the reference point to define a plane in which the line will lie. The grazing point will be computed starting with the line aligned with the specified direction, then rotating the line in the plane until the point of closest approach to the central body surface occurs at the specified altitude. An altitude specification of zero indicates that the line will graze the central body.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnPointCovarianceGrazing
member.summary: The point of closest approach to the surface of the specified position covariance ellipsoid surface along a defined direction. Position covariance must be available for a vehicle object to be considered a possible target for this option.

remarks.para: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the specified position covariance ellipsoid surface along a defined direction. Position covariance must be available for a vehicle object to be considered a possible target for this option. The position covariance ellipsoid is computed based on the specification of either a 3D probability level (probability that the true position is inside the ellipsoid boundary) or a scale factor which is applied to the one sigma ellipsoid. To define a grazing point, start by selecting the target object about which the covariance ellipsoid is centered and specify the means for computing the position covariance ellipsoid. Next define a reference point which will serve as the starting location for the line along which the grazing point will be computed. Next define a direction to be used in conjunction with the displacement vector from the selected target object to the reference point to define a plane in which the line will lie. The grazing point will be computed starting with the line aligned with the specified direction, then rotating the line in the plane until the point of closest approach to the covariance ellipsoid surface occurs at the specified distance. A distance specification of zero indicates that the line will graze the covariance ellipsoid.

member.name: M:AGI.STKVgt._IAgCrdnAxes.Transform(System.Object,AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnAxes,AGI.STKUtil.IAgCartesian3Vector)
member.summary:
Transforms the input vector from this axes into the output axes.
Consider a vector rotating and changing its magnitude in space. The vector's direction and magnitude as well as its time rate of change can be given at some specified time using Cartesian coordinates in one of VGT coordinate axes. The same vector at the same time will have different Cartesian coordinates with respect to different VGT coordinate axes. One set of coordinates can be obtained from the other using Transform methods defined for VGT coordinate axes: given time and coordinates with respect to one VGT coordinate axes, these methods output coordinates with respect to other axes. For example, consider a position vector of a satellite defined as displacement vector between the center of the Earth and the center of the satellite. When this position vector is viewed with respect to the Moon fixed axes, its magnitude remains the same because the vector is still a displacement vector between the Earth center and the center of satellite. Its Cartesian coordinates with respect to the Moon fixed axes will be different but not its magnitude.

param.name: Epoch
param.para: Specify an epoch. The method may throw an exception if the epoch parameter specified cannot be converted to a currently selected date unit.

param.name: OutputAxes
param.para: Specify an axes the input vector is transformed into.

member.name: M:AGI.STKVgt._IAgCrdnSystem.Transform(System.Object,AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnSystem,AGI.STKUtil.IAgCartesian3Vector)
member.summary:
Translates the position vector from this system into the output system.
Consider a point moving along its trajectory in space. The point's position and velocity can be given at some specified time using Cartesian coordinates in one of VGT coordinate systems. The same point at the same time will have different Cartesian coordinates with respect to a different VGT coordinate system. One set of coordinates can be obtained from the other using Transform methods defined for VGT coordinate systems: given time and coordinates with respect to one VGT coordinate system, these methods output coordinates with respect to another system. For example, consider a center point of a satellite. Its location in low Earth orbit can be given using Cartesian coordinates with respect to the ECEF coordinate system (ECEF means Earth Centered Earth Fixed). The same location is significantly farther away from the center of the Moon so its Cartesian coordinates in the Moon Centered Moon Fixed coordinate system will reflect a much greater distance from the Moon center.

param.name: Epoch
param.para: Specify an epoch. The method may throw an exception if the epoch parameter specified cannot be converted to a currently selected date unit.

param.name: OutputSystem
param.para: Specify a system to transform the position to.

member.summary: Translates the position and rate vectors from this system into the output system.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt._IAgCrdnPointGrazing
member.summary: Hidden interface for IAgCrdnPointGrazing

remarks.para: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the selected central body along a defined direction. To define a grazing point, start by defining a reference point which will serve as the starting location for the line along which the grazing point will be computed. Next define a direction to be used in conjunction with the position vector from the selected central body to the reference point to define a plane in which the line will lie. The grazing point will be computed starting with the line aligned with the specified direction, then rotating the line in the plane until the point of closest approach to the central body surface occurs at the specified altitude. An altitude specification of zero indicates that the line will graze the central body.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt._IAgCrdnPointCovarianceGrazing
member.summary: Hidden interface for IAgCrdnPointCovarianceGrazing

remarks.para: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the specified position covariance ellipsoid surface along a defined direction. Position covariance must be available for a vehicle object to be considered a possible target for this option. The position covariance ellipsoid is computed based on the specification of either a 3D probability level (probability that the true position is inside the ellipsoid boundary) or a scale factor which is applied to the one sigma ellipsoid. To define a grazing point, start by selecting the target object about which the covariance ellipsoid is centered and specify the means for computing the position covariance ellipsoid. Next define a reference point which will serve as the starting location for the line along which the grazing point will be computed. Next define a direction to be used in conjunction with the displacement vector from the selected target object to the reference point to define a plane in which the line will lie. The grazing point will be computed starting with the line aligned with the specified direction, then rotating the line in the plane until the point of closest approach to the covariance ellipsoid surface occurs at the specified distance. A distance specification of zero indicates that the line will graze the covariance ellipsoid.

member.summary: Returns a collection of availability intervals.

member.name: M:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnAxes.Transform(System.Object,AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnAxes,AGI.STKUtil.IAgCartesian3Vector)
member.summary:
Transforms the input vector from this axes into the output axes.
Consider a vector rotating and changing its magnitude in space. The vector's direction and magnitude as well as its time rate of change can be given at some specified time using Cartesian coordinates in one of VGT coordinate axes. The same vector at the same time will have different Cartesian coordinates with respect to different VGT coordinate axes. One set of coordinates can be obtained from the other using Transform methods defined for VGT coordinate axes: given time and coordinates with respect to one VGT coordinate axes, these methods output coordinates with respect to other axes. For example, consider a position vector of a satellite defined as displacement vector between the center of the Earth and the center of the satellite. When this position vector is viewed with respect to the Moon fixed axes, its magnitude remains the same because the vector is still a displacement vector between the Earth center and the center of satellite. Its Cartesian coordinates with respect to the Moon fixed axes will be different but not its magnitude.

param.name: Epoch
param.para: Specify an epoch. The method may throw an exception if the epoch parameter specified cannot be converted to a currently selected date unit.

param.name: OutputAxes
param.para: Specify an axes the input vector is transformed into.

member.name: M:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnAxesClass.Transform(System.Object,AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnAxes,AGI.STKUtil.IAgCartesian3Vector)
member.summary:
Transforms the input vector from this axes into the output axes.
Consider a vector rotating and changing its magnitude in space. The vector's direction and magnitude as well as its time rate of change can be given at some specified time using Cartesian coordinates in one of VGT coordinate axes. The same vector at the same time will have different Cartesian coordinates with respect to different VGT coordinate axes. One set of coordinates can be obtained from the other using Transform methods defined for VGT coordinate axes: given time and coordinates with respect to one VGT coordinate axes, these methods output coordinates with respect to other axes. For example, consider a position vector of a satellite defined as displacement vector between the center of the Earth and the center of the satellite. When this position vector is viewed with respect to the Moon fixed axes, its magnitude remains the same because the vector is still a displacement vector between the Earth center and the center of satellite. Its Cartesian coordinates with respect to the Moon fixed axes will be different but not its magnitude.

param.name: Epoch
param.para: Specify an epoch. The method may throw an exception if the epoch parameter specified cannot be converted to a currently selected date unit.

param.name: OutputAxes
param.para: Specify an axes the input vector is transformed into.

member.name: M:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnSystem.Transform(System.Object,AGI.STKVgt.IAgCrdnSystem,AGI.STKUtil.IAgCartesian3Vector)
member.summary:
Translates the position vector from this system into the output system.
Consider a point moving along its trajectory in space. The point's position and velocity can be given at some specified time using Cartesian coordinates in one of VGT coordinate systems. The same point at the same time will have different Cartesian coordinates with respect to a different VGT coordinate system. One set of coordinates can be obtained from the other using Transform methods defined for VGT coordinate systems: given time and coordinates with respect to one VGT coordinate system, these methods output coordinates with respect to another system. For example, consider a center point of a satellite. Its location in low Earth orbit can be given using Cartesian coordinates with respect to the ECEF coordinate system (ECEF means Earth Centered Earth Fixed). The same location is significantly farther away from the center of the Moon so its Cartesian coordinates in the Moon Centered Moon Fixed coordinate system will reflect a much greater distance from the Moon center.

param.name: Epoch
param.para: Specify an epoch. The method may throw an exception if the epoch parameter specified cannot be converted to a currently selected date unit.

param.name: OutputSystem
param.para: Specify a system to transform the position to.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnAngleDihedral
member.summary: An angle between two vectors about an axis.

remarks.para: The axis of rotation for the angle can be aligned with either Positive or Negative direction of the about vector. The angle is measured in the counterclockwise (or right-handed) sense about the selected direction of the axis. The range of values defined for the angle can be set either from 0 to 360 deg or from -180 to 180 deg.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnPointGrazing
member.summary: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the selected central body along a defined direction.

remarks.para: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the selected central body along a defined direction. To define a grazing point, start by defining a reference point which will serve as the starting location for the line along which the grazing point will be computed. Next define a direction to be used in conjunction with the position vector from the selected central body to the reference point to define a plane in which the line will lie. The grazing point will be computed starting with the line aligned with the specified direction, then rotating the line in the plane until the point of closest approach to the central body surface occurs at the specified altitude. An altitude specification of zero indicates that the line will graze the central body.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnPointGrazingClass
member.summary: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the selected central body along a defined direction.

remarks.para: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the selected central body along a defined direction. To define a grazing point, start by defining a reference point which will serve as the starting location for the line along which the grazing point will be computed. Next define a direction to be used in conjunction with the position vector from the selected central body to the reference point to define a plane in which the line will lie. The grazing point will be computed starting with the line aligned with the specified direction, then rotating the line in the plane until the point of closest approach to the central body surface occurs at the specified altitude. An altitude specification of zero indicates that the line will graze the central body.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnPointCovarianceGrazing
member.summary: The point of closest approach to the surface of the specified position covariance ellipsoid surface along a defined direction. Position covariance must be available for a vehicle object to be considered a possible target for this option.

remarks.para: The grazing point is the point of closest approach to the surface of the specified position covariance ellipsoid surface along a defined direction. Position covariance must be available for a vehicle object to be considered a possible target for this option. The position covariance ellipsoid is computed based on the specification of either a 3D probability level (probability that the true position is inside the ellipsoid boundary) or a scale factor which is applied to the one sigma ellipsoid. To define a grazing point, start by selecting the target object about which the covariance ellipsoid is centered and specify the means for computing the position covariance ellipsoid. Next define a reference point which will serve as the starting location for the line along which the grazing point will be computed. Next define a direction to be used in conjunction with the displacement vector from the selected target object to the reference point to define a plane in which the line will lie. The grazing point will be computed starting with the line aligned with the specified direction, then rotating the line in the plane until the point of closest approach to the covariance ellipsoid surface occurs at the specified distance. A distance specification of zero indicates that the line will graze the covariance ellipsoid.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnVectorEccentricity
member.summary: A vector directed from the center of the specified central body toward the nearest point of an elliptical orbit created from the motion of the specified point.

remarks.para: At any time, the orbit is fit to the current motion of the specified point according to the specified type orbital elements. Available types are: osculating, Brouwer-Lyddane long and short, and Kozai. The vector's magnitude is equal to the current eccentricity of the fit orbit.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnVectorEccentricityClass
member.summary: A vector directed from the center of the specified central body toward the nearest point of an elliptical orbit created from the motion of the specified point.

remarks.para: At any time, the orbit is fit to the current motion of the specified point according to the specified type orbital elements. Available types are: osculating, Brouwer-Lyddane long and short, and Kozai. The vector's magnitude is equal to the current eccentricity of the fit orbit.

member.name: T:AGI.STKVgt.AgCrdnVectorLineOfNodes
member.summary: Unit vector along the line of nodes - the line of intersection of the osculating orbit plane and the inertial equator of the specified central body.

remarks.para: Unit vector along the line of nodes - the line of intersection of the osculating orbit plane and the inertial equator of the specified central body. The vector is directed along the cross product of the Z-axis of the central body inertial coordinate system and the osculating orbit normal - the instantaneous osculating orbit of the specified point with respect to the specified central body.
